The constrained extrema of are &quot;critical points&quot; of the Lagrangian formula_56, but they are not necessarily &quot;local extrema&quot; of formula_37 (see below).

One may reformulate the Lagrangian as a Hamiltonian, in which case the solutions are local minima for the Hamiltonian. This is done in optimal control theory, in the form of Pontryagin&#x27;s maximum principle.

The fact that solutions of the method of Lagrange multipliers are not necessarily extrema of the Lagrangian, also poses difficulties for numerical optimization. This can be addressed by minimizing the &quot;magnitude&quot; of the gradient of the Lagrangian, as these minima are the same as the zeros of the magnitude, as illustrated in Example 5: Numerical optimization.

== Multiple constraints ==
The method of Lagrange multipliers can be extended to solve problems with multiple constraints using a similar argument. Consider a paraboloid subject to two line constraints that intersect at a single point. As the only feasible solution, this point is obviously a constrained extremum. However, the level set of formula_27 is clearly not parallel to either constraint at the intersection point (see Figure 3); instead, it is a linear combination of the two constraints&#x27; gradients. In the case of multiple constraints, that will be what we seek in general: The method of Lagrange seeks points not at which the gradient of formula_27 is a multiple of any single constraint&#x27;s gradient necessarily, but in which it is a linear combination of all the constraints&#x27; gradients.

Concretely, suppose we have formula_60 constraints and are walking along the set of points satisfying formula_61 Every point formula_62 on the contour of a given constraint function formula_63 has a space of allowable directions: the space of vectors perpendicular to formula_64 The set of directions that are allowed by all constraints is thus the space of directions perpendicular to all of the constraints&#x27; gradients. Denote this space of allowable moves by formula_65 and denote the span of the constraints&#x27; gradients by formula_66 Then formula_67 the space of vectors perpendicular to every element of formula_66

We are still interested in finding points where formula_27 does not change as we walk, since these points might be (constrained) extrema. We therefore seek formula_62 such that any allowable direction of movement away from formula_71 is perpendicular to formula_72 (otherwise we could increase formula_73 by moving along that allowable direction). In other words, formula_74 Thus there are scalars formula_75 such that
formula_76

These scalars are the Lagrange multipliers. We now have formula_60 of them, one for every constraint.

As before, we introduce an auxiliary function
formula_78
and solve
formula_79
which amounts to solving formula_80 equations in formula_81 unknowns.

The constraint qualification assumption when there are multiple constraints is that the constraint gradients at the relevant point are linearly independent.

==Modern formulation via differentiable manifolds==

The problem of finding the local maxima and minima subject to constraints can be generalized to finding local maxima and minima on a differentiable manifold formula_82 In what follows, it is not necessary that formula_83 be a Euclidean space, or even a Riemannian manifold. All appearances of the gradient formula_84 (which depends on a choice of Riemannian metric) can be replaced with the exterior derivative formula_85

===Single constraint===
Let formula_86 be a smooth manifold of dimension formula_87 Suppose that we wish to find the stationary points formula_88 of a smooth function formula_89 when restricted to the submanifold formula_90 defined by formula_91 where formula_92 is a smooth function for which is a regular value.

Let formula_93 and formula_94 be the exterior derivatives of formula_95 and formula_96. Stationarity for the restriction formula_97 at formula_98 means formula_99 Equivalently, the kernel formula_100 contains formula_101 In other words, formula_102 and formula_103 are proportional 1-forms. For this it is necessary and sufficient that the following system of formula_104 equations holds:
formula_105
where formula_106 denotes the exterior product. The stationary points formula_88 are the solutions of the above system of equations plus the constraint formula_108 Note that the formula_109 equations are not independent, since the left-hand side of the equation belongs to the subvariety of formula_110 consisting of decomposable elements.

In this formulation, it is not necessary to explicitly find the Lagrange multiplier, a number formula_111 such that formula_112

===Multiple constraints===
